ed Kingdom","of Y Faerdref,Llandrillo-yn-Ed,Merionethshire,Wales":"Llandrillo, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","1400–Female":"1400–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1337–Male":"1337–Overleden","1414–Male":"1414–Overleden","1385–1452":"1385–1452","1415–Female":"1415–Overleden","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1400":"1400","about 1414":"circa 1414","1452":"1452","1385":"1385","ABT    1337":"circa 1337","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Y Faerdref,Llandrillo-yn-Ed,Merionethshire,Wales":"Llandrillo, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1414–Male":"1414–Deceased","1385–1452":"1385–1452","1415–Female":"1415–Deceased","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1400":"1400","about 1414":"about 1414","1452":"1452","1385":"1385","ABT    1337":"about 1337","of Llwydiarth,Llannerch-y-medd,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Y Faerdref,Llandrillo-yn-Ed,Merionethshire,Wales":"Llandrillo, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Parcletis, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Breton, German, Dutch, Flemish, Danish, Greek, West Indian (mainly Haiti and Jamaica), and African (mainly Tanzania and Nigeria): from the personal name <i>Thomas</i>, of Biblical (New Testament) origin, from Aramaic <i>t’ōm’a</i>, a byname meaning ‘twin’. It was borne by one of the disciples of Christ, known for his scepticism about Christ's resurrection (John 20:24–29). The <i>Th-</i> spelling is organic, the initial letter of the name in the Greek New Testament being a theta. The English pronunciation as <i>t</i> rather than <i>th-</i> is the result of French influence from an early date. In Britain, the surname is widely distributed throughout the country, but especially common in Wales and Cornwall. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (e.g. Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Toma   and   Tuma  , Albanian   Toma   and   Thoma  , and Slavic surnames listed in 3 below), and their patronymics and other derivatives (e.g. Polish   Tomaszewski   and Slovenian <b>Tomažič</b>; see   Tomazic  ). In France, this surname is most common in the Vosges and Brittany. The name <i>Thomas</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Machan  ,   Mammen  , and   Oommen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Thomas</i> (see 1 above) as a surname.","Germanized or Americanized form of Polish   Tomas  , <b>Tomasz</b>, and <b>Tomaś</b>, Sorbian <b>Tomaš</b> (see also 4 below), Croatian <b>Tomaš</b> and   Tomas  , Slovenian <b>Tomaš</b> and <b>Tomaž</b>, Czech and Slovak <b>Tomáš</b>, all meaning ‘Thomas’."],"variants":[{"name":"Maas","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: from a short form of the personal name   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Mashak","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish <b>Maszak</b>: patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Tomasz</i> (see   Thomas  ) or possibly of a personal name beginning with <i>Ma-</i>. The surname <i>Maszak</i> is very rare in Poland.","In some cases also an Americanized form of Czech <b>Mašek</b> (see   Masek  ). Compare   Mashek  ."]},{"name":"Maschke","meanings":["German: from a Slavic-influenced (see below) pet form of the personal names   Thomas   (compare   Maas  ) or   Matthias  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mašk</b>, <b>Maška</b>, and <b>Maško</b>: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Domaš</i> or <i>Tomaš</i> (see   Thomas   3, 4), or of any name beginning with <i>Ma-</i>.","Germanized form of Czech <b>Mašek</b> (see   Masek  ) and Polish <b>Maszek</b>, both cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Toma","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Kamal, Nabil, Salem, Kamil, Safa, Samir, Adil, Adnan, Aziz, Bahjat, Basem, Bashar.  Japanese Hiroshi, Takeo, Hideo, Isako, Izumi, Junichi, Kenji, Kiyoko, Masakazu, Rikuo, Sachi, Shigeo.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Toma</i>, an equivalent of   Thomas  . Compare   Tomas  .","Italian, French, Polish, Slovak, and Hungarian: from a short, pet, or dialect form of a personal name equivalent to   Thomas   (Italian <i>Tommaso</i>, French <i>Thomas</i>, Polish <i>Tomasz</i>, Slovak <i>Tomáš</i>, Hungarian <i>Tamás</i>)."]},{"name":"Mask","meanings":["English: unexplained.","German: from a pet form of the personal name   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Masino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Ciro, Larraine.","Italian: from a short form of <b>Tommasino</b>, a pet form of thepersonal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]},{"name":"Mascio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Gino, Luigi, Paolo, Salvatore.","Italian:","(southern): from a variant of <i>Maso</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  ). Alternatively, perhaps from an Italianized form of the Albanian equivalent <i>Mashi</i>."]},{"name":"Masel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: from a pet form of   Thomas  ."]},{"name":"Masi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Mario, Vito, Carlo, Antonio, Alfonso, Armando, Filomena, Gerardo, Giovanni, Salvatore, Alfonse, Alfonsina, Amato, Anello, Canio, Emilio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Maso</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]},{"name":"Masiello","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carlo, Rocco, Angelo, Carmine, Franco, Salvatore, Antonio, Carmino, Domenic, Domenica, Francesco, Mauro.","Italian (mainly Naples): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i> (see   Thomas  )."]}]},{"name":"Efa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of several Anglicized forms of the Gaelic name Eithne . In the case of Queen Victoria's granddaughter Princess Ena (Victoria Eugénie Julia Ena,  1887–1969 ) it had a different origin: it was a misreading by the minister who baptized her off a handwritten note of the originally intended name   Eva .  In England, the name is remembered principally as that of the fearsome  Ena Sharples  in the television soap opera Coronation Street.  See also  Ina ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eithne","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Efa ferch Thomas was 